<main>

<!-- ══ ARTICLE HERO ══ -->
<section class="article-hero">
  <div class="hero-hex-grid"></div>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="article-hero-inner">
      <h1 class="article-title">Florida Hurricane Season: Does Your Patio Door Meet Code?</h1>
      <div class="hero-badge"><div class="hero-badge-dot"></div><span>Blog &middot; Impact &amp; Code</span></div>
      <p class="article-meta">Published <strong>June 2026</strong> &middot; <a href="/blog/">All articles</a></p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="article-wrap">
  <div class="container">

    <article class="article-body">
      <p>Hurricane season runs June through November. If you're in Florida and your patio door isn't rated for windborne debris, that's not a minor gap &mdash; it's a code issue in many counties, and insurance companies know it.</p>
      <p>This isn't about worst-case scenarios. It's about a specific building-code question that matters every time a named storm tracks toward Florida's coast: is your patio door rated for the zone your house is in?</p>

      <h2>What &ldquo;windborne debris zone&rdquo; actually means</h2>
      <p>Florida divides the state into wind zones based on the sustained wind speeds a structure is expected to face. In certain areas &mdash; called windborne debris regions &mdash; building code requires that openings like windows and doors either be protected by rated shutters or be made from impact-resistant materials.</p>
      <p>The most stringent designation is the High-Velocity Hurricane Zone, or HVHZ, which covers Miami-Dade and Broward counties. In the HVHZ, impact-rated doors and windows aren't a suggestion &mdash; they're a permit requirement for new construction and replacement projects. Other coastal counties have their own windborne debris requirements that fall short of HVHZ but still require rated products in many situations.</p>
      <p>The practical starting point: check your county's building department before you order a replacement door. The requirement varies not just by county but sometimes by exact location within a county.</p>

      <figure class="article-figure">
        <img src="/assets/images/blog/florida-impact-door-hurricane-code/1.png" alt="Florida wind zones — HVHZ (Miami-Dade &amp; Broward), high-risk coastal windborne debris regions, and lower-wind areas" loading="lazy" onerror="this.closest('figure').style.display='none'">
      </figure>

      <h2>What the certification actually tells you</h2>
      <p>When a door is tested and approved for use in Florida's windborne debris regions, it receives a Florida Building Code (FBC) product approval number. That number is public record. Anyone can search it at <a href="https://www.floridabuilding.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">floridabuilding.org</a> and pull the original approval document.</p>
      <p>The <a href="/doors/patio-doors/impact-hinged/">MP Doors Impact Hinged door</a> carries approval number <strong>FL-29714</strong>, currently at revision 15 (November 2025). The approval covers two sub-product configurations:</p>

      <div class="article-callout">
        <h3>MP Doors Impact Hinged &mdash; Florida approval at a glance</h3>
        <div class="cert-row"><b>Approval&nbsp;#</b><span><span class="cert-num">FL-29714</span> &nbsp;(rev. 15, Nov 2025)</span></div>
        <div class="cert-row"><b>29714.1</b><span>Standard windborne debris region configuration</span></div>
        <div class="cert-row"><b>29714.2</b><span>HVHZ configuration (Miami-Dade &amp; Broward counties)</span></div>
        <div class="cert-row"><b>Rating</b><span>DP +50 / &minus;50 &mdash; 50 lbs per square foot design pressure</span></div>
        <div class="cert-row"><b>Tested to</b><span>TAS 201, TAS 202, and TAS 203 (large-missile impact, cyclic wind pressure, uniform static air pressure)</span></div>
      </div>

      <p>Both configurations are rated at <strong>DP +50/&minus;50</strong> &mdash; meaning the door is tested to withstand positive and negative design pressure of 50 pounds per square foot. Testing was conducted to <strong>TAS 201, TAS 202, and TAS 203</strong>, which are the Florida-specific large-missile impact, cyclic wind pressure, and uniform static air pressure standards.</p>
      <p>To verify this yourself: go to <a href="https://www.floridabuilding.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">floridabuilding.org</a>, search product approval number FL29714, and pull the current record. The full test report is there.</p>
      <p>The takeaway: there are two versions of this door. If your project is in the HVHZ, you need to specifically confirm you're ordering the HVHZ-approved configuration. If you're outside the HVHZ but still in a windborne debris region, the standard configuration covers you &mdash; but confirm with your local building department first.</p>

      <figure class="article-figure">
        <img src="/assets/images/blog/florida-impact-door-hurricane-code/2.png" alt="Florida Building Code approval FL-29714 and the HVHZ certification for the impact-rated door" loading="lazy" onerror="this.closest('figure').style.display='none'">
      </figure>

      <h2>What's not impact-rated in the MP Doors lineup</h2>
      <p>Clarity matters here. The standard MP Doors gliding and hinged patio doors &mdash; the <a href="/doors/patio-doors/full-lite-gliding/">Full Lite Gliding</a>, <a href="/doors/patio-doors/shaker-gliding-2-3-lite/">Shaker Gliding</a>, <a href="/doors/patio-doors/hinged-full-lite/">Hinged Full Lite</a>, <a href="/doors/patio-doors/hinged-3-4-lite/">Hinged 3/4 Lite</a>, and <a href="/doors/patio-doors/shaker-hinged-2-3-lite/">Shaker Hinged 2/3 Lite</a> &mdash; are not impact-rated. They carry Florida Building Code approval for non-impact use in windborne debris regions with appropriate shutter protection, but they are not tested or certified as impact-resistant units on their own.</p>
      <p>If you're in a county or zone that requires impact-rated products without shutter alternatives, only the <a href="/doors/patio-doors/impact-hinged/">MP Doors Impact Hinged</a> qualifies.</p>

      <figure class="article-figure">
        <img src="/assets/images/blog/florida-impact-door-hurricane-code/3.png" alt="MP Doors patio door lineup — the impact-rated Impact Hinged versus the standard non-impact models" loading="lazy" onerror="this.closest('figure').style.display='none'">
      </figure>

      <h2>Before you order</h2>
      <p>Three things worth doing before you finalize a patio door order in Florida:</p>
      <p><strong>Check your zone.</strong> Your county building department can confirm whether your address falls in a windborne debris region and what the specific product requirements are. In Miami-Dade and Broward, the HVHZ requirement is nearly universal. In other coastal counties, it depends on distance from the coast and local wind speed maps.</p>
      <p><strong>Pull the approval record.</strong> Search FL29714 at <a href="https://www.floridabuilding.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">floridabuilding.org</a>. Compare the sub-product configurations against your permit requirements. Your contractor or permit office will be doing this check anyway &mdash; doing it yourself first means no surprises.</p>
      <p><strong>Confirm the configuration at checkout.</strong> The MP Doors Impact Hinged is available in the HVHZ-approved configuration. When ordering through The Home Depot, verify which configuration you're selecting. If you're unsure, MP Doors' customer service team can confirm the right choice for your project: <a href="tel:18883667717">1-888-366-7717</a> or <a href="mailto:customerservice@mpdoors.com">customerservice@mpdoors.com</a>.</p>

      <figure class="article-figure">
        <img src="/assets/images/blog/florida-impact-door-hurricane-code/4.png" alt="Florida Hurricane Season summary — know your zone, verify the FL-29714 certification, choose the right door, and the three steps before you order" loading="lazy" onerror="this.closest('figure').style.display='none'">
      </figure>

      <p>You can find the full certification documentation for the MP Doors Impact Hinged door &mdash; including the Florida Building Code approval &mdash; on the <a href="/doors/patio-doors/impact-hinged/">Impact Hinged door page</a>. The door itself is available at The Home Depot, in store and online.</p>

      <div class="article-cta">
        <h3>Impact-rated for Florida's toughest zones</h3>
        <p>The MP Doors Impact Hinged patio door &mdash; FL-29714, HVHZ-ready, DP +50/&minus;50. See the full specs or shop at The Home Depot.</p>
        <div class="cta-actions">
          <a href="/doors/patio-doors/impact-hinged/" class="button orange">See the Impact Hinged door &#8594;</a>
          <a href="https://www.homedepot.com" class="button white" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Shop at The Home Depot</a>
        </div>
      </div>

    </article>
  </div>
</div>

</main>
